---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
---

<Base title="gloria-christo">
  <div class="prose">
    <h1>gloria-christo</h1>
    <p class="lede">A personalized scripture-study skeleton. Anyone can inhabit it.</p>

    <p>
      Generic core (KJV + Brenton LXX + a four-frame reading methodology); per-user
      overlay (your chosen teacher, your analyses, your practice cycles) — forthcoming
      in later phases. What's transferable is not the specific content but the
      <em>way of working</em> with scripture across multiple reading frames at once.
    </p>

    <blockquote>
      <em>Let not the foot of pride come against me, and let not the hand of the wicked remove me.</em><br />
      — Psalm 36:11
    </blockquote>

    <h2>Browse</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <a href="/concordance/"><strong>Concordance</strong></a> — 64 KJV keyword
        verse-lists: every passage on love, faith, prayer, law, humility, pride, and more.
      </li>
      <li>
        <a href="/practices/"><strong>Practices</strong></a> — five operational disciplines:
        memorization, chanting, praying scripture, praying for humility.
      </li>
      <li>
        <a href="/texts/"><strong>Texts</strong></a> — close readings of specific passages
        (Hebrew + Greek where it serves the practice).
      </li>
      <li>
        <a href="/search/"><strong>Search</strong></a> — full-text across everything.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Start here</h2>
    <p>
      If new to this work: read <a href="/practices/praying-scripture/">praying-scripture</a> first
      (it orients the whole practice), then pick a keyword from the
      <a href="/concordance/">concordance</a> — <a href="/concordance/gann-love/">love</a> or
      <a href="/concordance/law-law/">law</a> are good first words — and start with
      <a href="/practices/memorization-priority/">what to memorize first</a>.
    </p>

    <h2>Six commitments</h2>
    <p>This project is shaped by six load-bearing commitments:</p>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>Anonymous.</strong> The work is the offering; the receipt is not required.</li>
      <li><strong>Open source.</strong> MIT-licensed. Forkable, cloneable, self-hostable.</li>
      <li><strong>Unpaid.</strong> No monetization, no premium tier, no ads, no engagement metrics.</li>
      <li><strong>Unkillable.</strong> Static-first; runs on any host or no host. Plain markdown — portable forever.</li>
      <li><strong>AI as calculator, human soul operates it.</strong> Future AI features are mechanical; they do not direct, counsel, or guide.</li>
      <li><strong>Bring your own API key.</strong> When AI ships, you provide your own key. No central billing. No central logging.</li>
    </ol>

    <h2>Public-domain texts</h2>
    <p>
      King James Version (1769 standard text). Brenton's English Septuagint (1851).
      Verse extraction is regex-based against a clean parsed text. The regex used
      appears in each concordance file's header for reproducibility.
    </p>
  </div>
</Base>
